{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"621fc8ff-f205-4e94-bc90-abf14204d22b","content":"The project directory doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a `dotnet tool`:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\nAdd these to your `MyMcpServer.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet package metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — this is the critical property that makes `dotnet pack` produce an installable tool.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (e.g., `dotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer` then run `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — it should already be since it's a stdio server.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get API key from https://www.nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\n```\n\nThen configure their MCP client to run `my-mcp-server` with stdio transport — no additional setup needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"abbeb71e-3d5c-46e8-9c69-b999bd7aeff3","outputTokens":519,"requestId":"7FC5:7D36C:61CE4E9:6AC75EF:69F15B98"},"id":"c11ee3f1-412e-44aa-a943-06db5885e601","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:15:14.586Z","parentId":"b6bdce76-1912-42c4-906e-e76089718975"}
